    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1915-08-31T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1915-08-31T00:00:00-05:00" n="1630"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1630">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 312.51/138.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">French Ambassador</gloss>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-08-31">
                            <hi rend="italic">August 31, 1915</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">My dear Mr. Ambassador</hi>: Referring to previous
                    correspondence in regard to 5,500 bales of cotton at Torreon, Mexico, consigned
                    to French firms in Mexico, I am pleased to inform you that the Department is in
                    receipt of a telegram from the American Consular Agent at Torreon, dated August
                    28, in which he states that the French Consular Agent at Torreon has informed
                    him that the cotton in question is still in storage at Torreon, under the
                    protection of the French Consular Agent. The telegram adds that the French
                    Consular Agent knows nothing of any contemplated confiscation of the cotton.</p>
                <p>I am [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Robert Lansing.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
